INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0ef646df-6e0a-4f90-9109-0a07638af774',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$ASP.NET Core EF Core vs Dapper — Picking the Right Tool and Killing N+1$escape$,
  $escape$ASP.NET Core gives you two dominant data access paths: EF Core (full ORM) and Dapper (micro-ORM/query builder). EF Core shines for complex domain models, migrations, and change tracking — use it with `DbContext` and model it with owned entities and value objects. Dapper wins for read-heavy endpoints where you want raw SQL performance with `IDbConnection.QueryAsync<T>`.

The N+1 problem bites hardest with EF Core's lazy loading. Disable it globally (`UseLazyLoadingProxies(false)`) and always eager-load with `.Include()`. For collections across large result sets, swap `.Include()` for `.AsSplitQuery()` to avoid the cartesian explosion that tanks performance on one-to-many joins.

For migrations, never run `dotnet ef database update` in production CI. Instead, generate idempotent scripts with `dotnet ef migrations script --idempotent` and apply them in your deployment pipeline. Use `MigrationBuilder.Sql()` for custom DDL that EF can't model. Keep migrations small and reversible — each one should have a valid `Down()` method.$escape$,
  $escape$// Eager load with split query to avoid cartesian product
var posts = await _db.Posts
    .Where(p => p.AuthorId == userId)
    .Include(p => p.Tags)
    .Include(p => p.Comments)
    .AsSplitQuery()
    .AsNoTracking()
    .ToListAsync();

// Dapper for high-throughput read endpoint
var feed = await _conn.QueryAsync<PostDto>(
    "SELECT id, title, summary FROM posts WHERE is_published = TRUE ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 20",
    commandTimeout: 5);$escape$,
